Don’t tell me I can’t…I will prove you wrong!  Did it 🥊

I’m here to tell you, YOU can too!  It takes a lot of failure to succeed.  It takes a growth mindset and a belief in yourself.  We will face adversity.  You miss 100% of the shots you don’t take.👊

How did I get here?  I surrounded myself with the BEST!  I connected with family, mothers, friends and colleagues with similar adversity and the same mindset.  It works! 

Recently, I connected with a mom going through a similar situation as we did with Miles.  She reached out, which I WANT ANYONE & EVERYONE to do if they need it.  We have connected and I know she and her child will do very well.  She is a wonderful advocate & mother.  Everyone will endure some sort of adversity in their role as a mother, employee, athlete etc…so set yourself up for success.  Connect with people who are positive and uplifting.  Those that will help you face adversity with support and encourage you to keep going.  That’s the difference.  We aren’t in this alone.  We are in this together, please feel free to reach out to me.

Happy Wednesday!

I felt like I may have lost my mind & crossed the line! 🤪🤪🤪🤪🤪

The reason behind the blog…

My 2nd born child, Miles.  When faced with his diagnosis, as a family we chose to leave our jobs and focus on his therapies.  We built this site to earn income and spread awareness.  We did it!  And we will continue to thrive. 🪴

Today is Rare Disease Day!  Feb 28th 🪴

Miles has the rare disease, Jordan’s Syndrome and this is a good resource: https://jordansguardianangels.org/category/our-global-community/ for accurate and positive information.  Remember that these disorders are a spectrum and can be mild to severe, so each child is different. 🪴

3.5 years ago we were graced with the presence of our #mightymiles and we were so grateful.  What we did not know is that we had an uphill battle to climb, but y’all I am happy to report that this kid is a fighter. 

He is doing all the things! 
He runs, laughs, communicates, attends school and his receptive language is on point!  He is simply amazing.  More importantly he has taught us SO much!

He has taught us to live in the moment, takes chances, live a happy fulfilled life.  Love unconditionally, laugh uncontrollably, snuggle every single day and find the silver lining in EVERYTHING.  We are a closer, happier and more empathetic family.  I started to live after having my boys.  I’m so thankful for both of them and their love for each other. 

Thank you for supporting us and following our journey!  We are so grateful 🪴

The reason behind the business Heels & Happiness. 

My husband and I went through loss and had difficulty having children. 

After a lot of help and support, at 35 years old, I had Parker!  It brought us great joy to be parents.  We knew we wanted more, however, my age could present issues. 

And at 6 months post Parker’s birth we found out we were pregnant again.  It was the best surprise ever.  We thought that this would allow us to have more after Miles-yay!!!! 

At 38 weeks Miles, was born with a full head of hair and a quiet demeanor.  We were a family of 4!  I had a much more difficult time with postpartum anxiety this time around, however, I had a great support group so it was manageable.

By two months, things seemed to be different with Miles.  I wasn’t sure if it was being the second child and the closeness in age that he seemed to be behind.  So, I reached out to the Pediatrician. 

She was awesome and said we’d check back at 3 months.  By 3 months I was certain something was different, and requested an evaluation.  He would sleep during nursing.  He seemed exhausted and lethargic. He also was very “floppy.” 

Fast forward, we miss milestones and he is diagnosed with Hypotonia (low-tone.). 

Both of us (my husband and I) take time off to help with therapies and testing. 

At 3 years old, he is finally diagnosed with Jordan’s Syndrome.  Obviously, with that is a fear that he may struggle in life, but with the diagnosis came clarity and understanding. 

Life after a diagnosis…the reason for THIS REEL.  Yes, therapies are time consuming and difficult at times.  But it’s SO WORTH IT. 

Both Parker and Miles are EXACTLY what my husband and I were searching for.  We did need more.  They complete us. 

Miles is running, communicating and the most loving child I have ever met. He brings us so much joy. 

Parker is the best older brother.  Brilliant, kind and empathetic.  We fell for these two boys and we could never go back. 

“I’m falling” forever.  So, to any Mama or family going through finding a diagnosis or raising a A-typical child.  I’m here to tell you, it’s worth it.  You will find peace, joy and belonging.  I am the happiest I’ve ever been. More ⬇️

At some point we all face adversity, some more difficult then others, however our strength lies in your ability to learn and grow from the situation even if it takes time. 

I remember the day the neurologist told us Miles was missing so many milestones and his low tone was very substantial.  I asked if he would walk or talk…and he said we won’t know, until that time comes, but he wasn’t optimistic. 

How do you live with this?  How do you move forward?  Why does he have to experience this?  Why can’t it be me?????? 

My knees buckled as I screamed in a full office of patients and fell to the floor.  I remember my family picking me up off the floor. 

I remember the Neurologist delivering the news and walking away…I remember the room turning black, as the walls caved in on me. 

I slept on the floor of my oldest child’s room.  I prayed and begged for his cure.  I begged for this to be wrong.  I didn’t know how to be his mom. 

Then, I accepted it and fought for him.  I advocated and decided that one person wouldn’t determine his capabilities.  I loved Miles the day I took him in my arms, and this wouldn’t take that away from me.  I took him to every therapy, left work and devoted myself to both of my boys entirely. 

Well, he IS THRIVING!  He is running and this last week he began to speak!  Screaming mama, map, backpack (thanks Dora!) and more.  This is just the beginning. 

So, grab your fast car…and find the purpose of your adversity or pain.  I am here to tell you that the other side is so beautiful. 💕

I’m thankful for the support and strength my own mama gave me. 💪🏻

4…four years of loving you.  Wow, it sure does go by quick.  So, to be totally transparent, I used to worry about your future.  When we received your diagnosis of Jordan’s Syndrome (as of 2019 only 23 people reported in medical literature) it seemed so scary, rare and debilitating for us to navigate.  Well, it was quite the contrary.  Being your mother has required me to learn and grow.  To advocate for your needs and leave fear behind.  To believe in you and to follow your lead.  Being your mother is an absolute gift.  I’ve exchanged worry for belief.  I believe in you and in our family.  I always will. 💙

I have learned that Miles is overstimulated at times with too many people, so we have limit the amount or let him have a safe space.  I’ve also learned that schedules and routines help ease him when he is overwhelmed.  I’m getting better at this, too. 

Miles is the most loving, kind and genuine child you’ll ever meet.  He is curious and LOVES one on one time with friends.  The day before his birthday he brought his big brother’s list of colors and animals for Kindergarten to me.  He pointed to the words (in black and white print) and correctly stated each color and animal!  It blew me away!  It was this moment my fear for his future truly faded.  He is bright, loving and he is perfectly ours.  I am not that mama anymore.  I’m not fearful of the future.  I’m excited and ready, because this is just the beginning, and I’m so proud of that little boy who fought to hold up his head at 9 months, took his first steps at 2 years old, and has now begun talking (some words) and reading at age 4!  You are our fighter, and we will continue to shatter the barriers that come with a rare disease!  You continue to inspire us and make us proud.  I am so LUCKY to be your mama.  Happy Birthday Miles!  You are rare star in our sky.  You will always shine brightly.

It took a minute to get here, but I made it.  This is not to say it’s been easy or beautiful.  It’s been messy, challenging, and sometimes so debilitating it nearly broke me. But, I never gave up.  I NEVER STOP believing.  I can still hear the Neurologist & Geneticist telling me the odds of my son walking/talking or socializing etc…was very slim.  I just knew that couldn’t be the case.  I wouldn’t accept that for his journey..or ours.  So what did I do? 

1. Stopped researching the disease
2. Started researching success stories that went against the “odds”
3. Developed a plan with doctors and specialists
4.  Moved schools and took my son with me.
5. Invested in myself-exercise, diet and made time for my friends to stay positive, healthy & happy
6.  Invested in my marriage, continued date night and got several reliable sitters to help during burnout (built a business to pay for them) 
7. Built a business around my passion-styling 💓
8. Built a community of other mamas going through similar journeys @mamabearforrare (the first mom I reached out to-I highly recommend doing this)  You are NOT alone. 🫶🏻

Also, I edit while chasing Miles as he RUNS around, so pardon my mistakes.  This is not an essay, just an IG post (TIA) 

How it helped….Miles is doing everything a child would do just a little late on his time.  He has defied his diagnosis and triumphed tremendously.  We are flourishing as a family (not perfect to, but imperfectly beautiful 🤩 

I share this because of you are experiencing something debilitating, hang tight and you will get to the other side.  Hopefully, some of these ideas may help. 

We now await Miles’ EEG results with optimism and strength. 🫶🏻

P.S. Miles is also reading words out of books. 🤯
